  "summary": "Detective Inspector Dick Hakast arrives at 19 Wilbraham Crescent to investigate the murder of a man found dead on the floor, who appears to have been stabbed approximately thirty minutes prior. The house is owned by Millee Pema-Chhoe (also referred to as Miss Pembleton, Miss Pema, Miss Pemah, or Miss Permshaw), a teacher at the Allenburg Institute who instructs disabled children in blind script.\n\nIn the kitchen, Hakast interviews Hilary Webber, a stenographer from the Cavendish Document Printing Agency. Webber explains that her employer, Miss Martin, sent her to the house at 3:00 p.m. following a request she claims was made by Miss Pema-Chhoe. Webber admits she discovered the body after turning a sofa and touched the corpse, leaving her hands covered in blood. She appears visibly shaken and fearful. During the questioning, Webber notes a strange discrepancy regarding the house's clocks: while the cuckoo clock struck three, other clocks in the house were set nearly an hour ahead. Webber claims she entered the house because Miss Pema-Chhoe told her to come in, despite the two having never spoken before.\n\nAfter dismissing Webber to the dining room, Hakast prepares to interview Miss Pema-Chhoe. As he approaches, she demonstrates her blindness by feeling her way to a chair. Before the interview begins, Miss Pema-Chhoe questions Hakast regarding the identity and presence of Colin Lamb, the man who had been at the scene.",
